\n\n      // For each pivot row r, the pivot value would be:\n      // (rhs[r] - contrib1[r] - contrib2[r]) mod p\n      // We need contrib1 such that the total sum is minimized.\n      // Total = freeSum1 + freeSum2 + sum of pivot values\n      // pivot value for row r = (rhs[r] - contrib1[r] - contrib2[r]) mod p\n      // sum of pivot values = sum_r (rhs[r] - contrib1[r] - contrib2[r]) mod p\n\n      // The needed contrib1 vector: for each r, we need (rhs[r] - contrib2[r]) mod p\n      // Then pivot[r] = (needed[r] - contrib1[r]) mod p\n      // Total pivot sum = sum_r ((needed[r] - contrib1[r]) mod p)\n\n      // We can't just pick the contrib1 that makes all pivots 0 (that would minimize pivot sum to 0)\n      // because not all contrib1 vectors may be achievable. We need to iterate over\n      // all contrib1 vectors in our table.\n\n      // Actually, the minimum pivot sum for a given contrib1 is achieved when each\n      // (needed[r] - contrib1[r]) mod p is as small as possible. Since these are determined\n      // by the combo, we just evaluate.\n\n      // However, iterating over ALL half1 table entries for each half2 is too expensive\n      // if both halves are large. The table could have up to modulus^half1 entries.\n      // With half1 = 20 and modulus = 2, that's 1M entries -- feasible.\n      // With modulus = 97 and half1 = 3, that's ~900K -- feasible.\n      // With modulus = 97 and half1 = 20, that's 97^20 -- way too many.\n\n      // For very large cases, we'd need a smarter approach. But given practical constraints\n      // (40 buttons, 40 counters), rank is typically close to 40, leaving few free vars.\n\n      // For now, check if we can find the exact match (all pivot values = 0)\n      const needed = new Array(rank);\n      for (let r = 0; r < rank; r++) {\n        needed[r] = (rhs[r] - contrib2[r] + modulus * 100) % modulus;\n      }\n\n      // Look up exact match first (this gives pivot sum = 0)\n      const exactKey = contribKey(needed)